{"news_desk": "National", "print_page": "16", "section_name": "U.S.", "subsection_name": null, "byline": {"original": "By RICHARD FAUSSET and CAMPBELL ROBERTSON", "person": [{"rank": 1, "role": "reported", "firstname": "Richard", "organization": "", "lastname": "FAUSSET"}, {"rank": 2, "role": "reported", "firstname": "Campbell", "organization": "", "lastname": "ROBERTSON"}]}, "abstract": "Falcon Heights, Minn, and Baton Rouge, La, are developing carefully planned responses to police shootings of Philando Castile and Alton Sterling, in contrast to bungled and angry responses to past shootings like that of Michael Brown in Ferguson, Mo; reactions reflect growing awareness among small communities of public spotlight that follows such crises.", "type_of_material": "News", "word_count": "1116", "lead_paragraph": "As high-profile police shootings of black men, like those this week, continue, communities are veering from the tight-lipped and sometimes antagonistic reactions of the past.", "pub_date": "2016-07-08T00:00:00Z", "document_type": "article", "slideshow_credits": null, "headline": {"main": "Communities Work to Avoid Provocations in Response to Shootings", "print_headline": "Communities Work to Avoid Provocations in Response to Shootings"}, "snippet": "As high-profile police shootings of black men, like those this week, continue, communities are veering from the tight-lipped and sometimes antagonistic reactions of the past....", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/07/08/us/08script-web1/08script-web1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"widewidth": "190", "wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/07/08/us/08script-web1/08script-web1-thumbWide.jpg"}, "type": "image", "width": 190, "subtype": "wide"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2016/07/08/us/08script-web1/08script-web1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "400", "xlarge": "images/2016/07/08/us/08script-web1/08script-web1-articleLarge.jpg"}, "type": "image", "width": 600, "subt